explanation: To determine whether any case labels (and thus statements in OS_CleanUpObject) are unreachable you must know exactly what return values OS_IdentifyObject can produce and how those values are defined. • OS_IdentifyObject — the switch discriminant; you need its implementation/behavior to know which case values can actually be returned for a given object_id. • OS_ObjectIdToType_Impl — OS_IdentifyObject delegates to this underlying mapping in the static graph; its logic determines the mapping from object_id to object-type values. • osal_id_t — the type/representation of object_id can affect the mapping and validity checks in the above functions; include its definition. • OS_OBJECT_TYPE_* constants (OS_TASK, OS_QUEUE, OS_BINSEM, OS_COUNTSEM, OS_MUTEX, OS_MODULE, OS_TIMEBASE, OS_TIMECB, OS_STREAM, OS_DIR, OS_CONDVAR) — the exact numeric values and the full set of defined object-type enumerators/macros are needed to decide if each case label in the switch is a possible/defined return value or is impossible (hence unreachable).
